rt</a> appeared first on <a\nrel="nofollow" href="https://extendd.com">Extendd</a>.</p> ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Austin Passy";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8554:"<p><strong>This plugin requires <a\nhref="https://easydigitaldownloads.com/?ref=116" title="Easy Digital Downloads">Easy Digital Downloads</a> > which can be downloaded for FREE in the WordPress repo.</strong></p><h2>Abandoned Carts</h2><p>If you are like me, you check you WordPress stats, Google Analytic&#8217;s or what ever statistical application you might use. And if you are selling digital products I am sure you trying to find the balance between site visitors and sales. This plugin might be a small bridge between the two. Abandoned Cart WordPress.</p><h3>A simple solution</h3><p>This plugin only requires one thing to be effective. The visitor needs to enter there email address on the checkout page. They don&#8217;t have to follow through with the checkout process (though that what we&#8217;re all looking for).</p><h3>How does it work?</h3><p>When a visitor has items in the cart, and visits the checkout page, Abandoned Cart goes to work. Whey the user enters their email address the plugin saves that email address to the database to be used later. If the checkout process is completed then that email address is removed from the Abandoned Cart database.</p><h3>How to use it</h3><p>Be sure that Easy Digital Downloads is activated and you&#8217;re running version greater than <code>1.5</code>.</p><ol><li><strong>Settings page</strong><ul><li>Coupon discount: <em>information about your discount</em>.</li><li>Coupon code: <em>pulls in all discount coupon if any from EDD</em>.</li><li>Email subject: <em>the email subject line</em>.</li><li>Email body: <em>the email subject body</em>.<p><strong>*Notes on the body</strong><br\n/> There is a template and template codes which when present or omitted prints out the proper settings. Available as of <code>v.1.2.1</code>:</p><ul><li>###ADD_TO_CART_LINK###</li><li>###COUPON_DISCOUNT###</li><li>###COUPON###</li><li>###SITENAME###</li><li>###SITEURL###</li></ul></li><p></ul></li></ol><p>That&#8217;s it! Sit back and collect abandoned cart information and make the re-capture sales! You can thank me later.</p><p\nclass="note"> Emails are collected automatically but until a auto-cron is built in a future release you have to manually email each user. Which is still as simple as hovering over the user and clicking <em><a\nhref="https://extendd-frostywebdesigns.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/edd-abandoned-cart-abandoned-emails-2.png" class="fancybox">email user</a></em>, WordPress handles the rest with the built in wp_mail function.</p><form\nid="edd_purchase_8017" class="edd_download_purchase_form" method="post"><div\nclass="edd_price_options"><ul><li\nid="edd_price_option_8017_2-5sites" itemprop="offers" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Offer"><label\nfor="edd_price_option_8017_1"><input\ntype="radio"  checked=''checked'' name="edd_options[price_id][]" id="edd_price_option_8017_1" class="edd_price_option_8017" value="1"/>&nbsp;<span\nclass="edd_price_option_name" itemprop="description">2 - 5 Sites</span><span\nclass="edd_price_option_sep">&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;</span><span\nclass="edd_price_option_price" itemprop="price">&#36;50.00</span></label></li><li\nid="edd_price_option_8017_singlesite" itemprop="offers" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Offer"><label\nfor="edd_price_option_8017_0"><input\ntype="radio"  name="edd_options[price_id][]" id="edd_price_option_8017_0" class="edd_price_option_8017" value="0"/>&nbsp;<span\nclass="edd_price_option_name" itemprop="description">Single Site</span><span\ncla